<p><img class="tex" alt="
\hbox{New price } y \hbox{ years later} = \hbox{old price } \times \left(1+\frac{\hbox{inflation}}{100}\right)^{y}
" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/c/8/9c861dc393c019e1ad8a3f250c826403.png" /></p>
<p><img class="tex" alt="
\hbox{Monthly inflation } = 100 \times \left(\left(1+\frac{\hbox{inflation}}{100}\right)^{\frac{1}{12}} -1\right)
" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/5/2/a5245358f03cbde042cff39f71296603.png" /></p>
<p><img class="tex" alt="
\hbox{Price doubling time}  = \frac{\log_{10} 2}{\log_{10} \left(1+ \frac{\hbox{inflation}}{100}\right)}
" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/c/5/ac547b03d6c937cdbb48fded0ae2df53.png" /></p>
<p><img class="tex" alt="
\hbox{Years per added zero of the price } = \frac{1}{\log_{10} \left(1+ \frac{\hbox{inflation}}{100}\right)}
" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/d/b/0dba97069fbd177dd577cbce9fa130fb.png" /></p>
<p>Often, at <a href="/wiki/Redenomination" title="Redenomination" class="mw-redirect">redenominations</a>, three zeroes are cut from the bills. It can be read from the table that if the (annual) inflation is for example 100%, it takes 3.32 years to produce one more zero on the price tags, or 3 × 3.32 = 9.96 years to produce three zeroes. Thus can one expect a redenomination to take place about 9.96 years after the currency was introduced.</p>
